node.text:
Only One launched a year ago today in the middle of a global pandemic that left many feeling isolated, but also, that underscored our interdependence with each other and with nature. 

Over the past year, this community embraced that connection and our collective responsibility to protect the ocean and the planet we all call home. Millions of supporters took action, helping to advance advocacy efforts and contributing to support ocean stories and solutions around the world and shape a better, shared future for all of us and generations to come.

They have made tremendous progress in the first year, and they’re just getting started. We hope you'll dive even deeper into the work in the years to come, and if you haven't already, consider joining the nearly 8,000 members of The Tide community who are supporting this work through their monthly contributions: only.one/tide

node.text: Day 2 of our Tiger Shark Expedition and we have already encountered 12 Tiger sharks, 2 Thresher sharks, Black tip, Silver tip and White tip reef sharks!! We are now on our way to do our 2nd Tiger shark dive, stay tuned on our story for details! It is 30 degrees Celsius in the water and the weather has been gorgeous! What a beautiful time to be here, email us at info@discoversharkstours.com to join our next expedition September 18th - 25th, limited space available! Let’s go! 🦈 #discoversharksexpeditions

The expedition will be broadcast live on @discoversharks 🎥Click the link in our bio for more details

node.text: This is the most tragic thing I’ve ever filmed: a pod of dolphins swimming through a giant oil spill. The spill is spanning an area covering more than 50 miles, and it is lurking just off the coast of San Diego. On today’s extended trip we made our way to our reliable Blue Whale hotspot near San Clemente Island and we were shocked when the whales seemingly vanished. Just 24 hours earlier this zone was full of the feeding giants. It was then that we began making our way south, and soon made this shocking discovery. Tragic doesn’t begin to cover it. For more than 50 miles the ocean was covered in a thick sheen of oil, a devastating tragedy for the environment. We know very little at this time, and we are trying to make these images go viral in hopes of getting some answers as to how this happened. More shocking yet, 70+ miles away back in coastal San Diego, the local whale watching boats reported an area thick with oil encroaching on the local waters as well. I truly hope this isn’t as bad as it appears, but if this oil is already in an area that spans at a minimum of 70 miles, we could have a catastrophe of unimaginable scale on our hands. Please share this video with your followers and tag people, celebrities, influencers and news media that need to see and share it too: WE NEED ANSWERS BEFORE ANY MORE MARINE LIFE SUFFERS! We’ve reached out to NOAA, the Coast Guard, and the EPA. We hope to have an update soon. Video and caption by our friend @dolphindronedom #saveouroceans

Reposted from @jungle_doctor One of the biggest challenges faced by veterinarians and wildlife conservationists alike is that you are often working with a moving target. But this takes it to a whole new level! This amazing video by Dr @simonjpierce shows the collection of blood plasma in a free-swimming whale shark in the wild by @dr.al.dove, who is one of the pioneers of this method.
This new technique provides the ability to monitor the health of free-swimming animals, including learning more about their reproductive cycles and – by extension – their conservation needs. The hope is that this can be used to support better conservation decisions and reverse the trend of globally declining whale shark populations. And, for an endangered species, developments like these are crucial.
For anyone who loves whale sharks as much as I do, Drs Dove and Pierce have just released the first scientific textbook on whale sharks – “Whale Sharks - Biology, Ecology and Conservation”. I’m in awe of their work, and of these amazing animals, and I look forward to the day I next find myself in the water with them!

Only One launched a year ago today in the middle of a global pandemic that left many feeling isolated, but also, that underscored our interdependence with each other and with nature. 

Over the past year, this community embraced that connection and our collective responsibility to protect the ocean and the planet we all call home. Millions of supporters took action, helping to advance advocacy efforts and contributing to support ocean stories and solutions around the world and shape a better, shared future for all of us and generations to come.

They have made tremendous progress in the first year, and they’re just getting started. We hope you'll dive even deeper into the work in the years to come, and if you haven't already, consider joining the nearly 8,000 members of The Tide community who are supporting this work through their monthly contributions: only.one/tide

Via @seashepherd 🛑WARNING - GRAPHIC IMAGES!🛑

1428 DOLPHINS KILLED IN FAROE ISLANDS

We normally strive to keep our IG feed to the beautiful, positive and inspirational moments from our ships and campaigns - however, extenuating circumstances calls for spreading this incredibly awful news, as the whalers of the Faroe Islands have set a grim record. 

Sunday, September 12th, 1428 Atlantic White-Sided dolphins were killed by local whalers in the Faroe Islands, possibly setting the record for the largest single slaughter of cetaceans in recorded history. The entire superpod was killed, including pregnant females and young. 

With the size of the pod, too few boats, and far too few people, the hunt was more chaotic than usual, undoubtedly causing severe distress and suffering to the animals, including several dolphins that were maimed by the propellers of the chasing boats while trying to avoid capture.

"These animals are the exact same that people around the world dream of meeting in the wild, never mind a superpod of this size. Yet, in the Faroe Islands they are welcomed with knives and hooks" said Lukas Erichsen of Sea Shepherd Scandinavia

READ the full story in @seashepherd’s bio!

📸 First photo is kindly donated by Kyla McLay - these dolphins were not involved in the slaughter. 
📸 Grind photos by Sea Shepherd
